  1. Split your data set into a training set containing 100 observations and a test set containing 900 observations:
split <- sample.split(data$Y, SplitRatio = 0.9)
dataTrain <- subset(data, split == "TRUE")
dataTest <- subset(data, split == "FALSE")
  1. Perform best subset selection on the training set, and plot the training set MSE associated with the best model of each size:
regfit.best <- regsubsets(Y ~ ., dataTrain, nvmax = 20)
reg.summary <- summary(regfit.best)
reg.summary$rsq

  1. Create a plot displaying \(\sqrt{\sum_{j=1}^p(\beta_j-\hat\beta^r_j)^2}\) for a range of values of \(r\), where \(\hat\beta^r_j\) is the \(j\)-th coefficient estimate for the best model containing \(r\) coefficients.
res <- vector()
for (i in 1:20){
  r.best <- coef(regfit.best, i)
  t <- 0 
  for (j in 2:(i+1)){
    t <- t + (r.best[j]-beta[[names(r.best)[j]]])^2
  }
  res <- append(res, sqrt(t))
}
plot(res, t = 'l')
